Fluid flow in the continuum regime is governed by the continuity equation and the Navier–Stokes momentum equations which are valid for unsteady, compressible, and viscous flow. For a small air-gap separating the plate from base, the squeeze film flow is predominantly two-dimensional (i.e. in the x-y plane). The Reynolds equation, defined under the following assumptions:


No external forces act on the film;

No inertial effects;

The structure oscillates with small amplitude and the main flow is driven by pressure gradients in the x and y directions;

No slip flow occurs at the planar boundaries;

No variation of pressure across the fluid film;

The flow is laminar; no vortex flow and no turbulence occur anywhere in the film. Fully developed flow is considered within the gap;

Different assumptions can also be important for specific types of fluid. For air, flow is assumed to be isothermal;
